[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/blackwood"]
[Student "S"]
{With a 20 point balanced hand you open 2NT. What do you rebid after partner jumps to 4\C? 

The 4\C bid is Gerber and your correct response with 2 Aces is 4\S. Partner now bids 6NT and since he is the Captain you pass.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "4"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "All"]
[Deal "E:84.AJT863.63.A75 T62.75.987.KT963 AK.K942.KQJT54.8 QJ9753.Q.A2.QJ42"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "6H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
2H pass 4NT pass 5H pass 6H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 4, chOption: E, chBasis: N, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 0, nRot: 1, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "00f62fd8f103bb91ba3893b9c3b90e500eb0e1271618b0921c08f2a83fcec17c"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/blackwood"]
[Student "S"]
{Partner opens a Weak 2-bid and catches you with a blockbuster. The only thing you want to know about his hand now is how many Aces he has. So you bid 4NT. Partner answers 5\H.  

That makes it simple, with 2 Aces you bid a confident 6\H. If he had 1 Ace you would have bid an also confident 5\H. If he had zero Aces you would have been in a spot of trouble. And if he had 3 Aces you would have asked him how he could open a Weak-2 with that many points.}

